The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Metro | The City Diary
                                                                                                                         3                                                                                      The City Diary
                Usha Das, 45, was run over by a chartered bus at the Behala tram depot crossing on Monday evening. Police said the resident of Pearabagan was crossing the road when she was hit by an autorickshaw and then mowed down by the bus. The bus was impounded but the driver fled.   n Sunday night, a motorcyclist died after being hit by a truck near Girish Park. Parthasarathi Ghosh, 29, an employee of a private firm, was returning home to Battala when the mishap occurred. The truck was impounded and the driver arrested.     The condition of Esha Dutta, who met with a mishap on Ballygunge Circular Road early on Sunday, was critical on Monday. The woman in her mid-20s was admitted to CMRI with head and chest injuries. Esha was driving home to Garia when her car collided rammed into a signal post after colliding with a vehicle. Two men who were in the same car suffered minor injuries.    The first issue of The Kolkata Protector, a bimonthly magazine of Calcutta police, was launched by police chief Gautam Mohan Chakrabarti at the Calcutta Book Fair on Monday. The magazine contains the office telephone numbers of all senior officers of Lalbazar and all police stations in the city.    A Calcutta-Chennai Paramount Airways flight returned to the city within seven minutes of take-off at 1.32pm after it hit a bird on Monday. The flight later left at 2.35pm.     Sreejit Das, 42, who was arrested on Sunday for fraud, was produced in court on Monday and remanded in police custody for 10 days. Das had allegedly duped Somenath Manna by promising him a job.     A security guard working at Satya Bharati Bani Niketan School in Barasat was beaten up by goons early on Monday and some school documents were stolen. Police said guard Palan Ghosh, 37, was admitted to Calcutta Medical College and Hospital. The school authorities said documents relating to the schools accounts had been stolen.                                                                                                                                                  
